<section xml:id="lesson5_4" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Calculating Quantum Gate Results</title>

<p> There are two pieces you need to be able to calculate quantum gates:</p>

<p> 1. How are gates represented? </p>

<p> 2. Given a starting state and a gate, how do you calculate the resulting state? </p>

<section xml:id="quantum gate representation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Quantum Gate Representation</title>

<p>
     Quantum gates are represented as a matrix, which is a grid of numbers.
     Quantum gates are always squares - that is, the length is always equal the 
     width. They are also of pre-determined size. A gate that operates on n bits 
     has length and width 2^n. That means a 2-qubit gate is a 4x4 matrix, and a 3-qubit 
     gate is an 8x8 matrix.
     </p>

     <p> Here are a few gates and their representations. But we can't do anything useful with 
     them until we learn to calculate with them!!</p>

 <p><image source="L5.4.nothmatrices.png" width="30%" /></p>

     </section>

